  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n3. State Laws:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\n4. Key Requirements:\n- Financial institutions must report cash transactions over $10,000\n- Suspicious activity must be reported\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\n5. Regulatory Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)\n- Federal banking regulators\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the concealment of the origins of illegally obtained money.",
